Technologies over the contextual linking components in AdSense and Google Toolbar just got more complicated, as the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit has overturned part of a lower court's ruling that was in Google's favor. Madison, Wisc.-based HyperPhrase first filed suit against Google in April 2006. In the previous ruling, the U.S. District Court for the Western
District of Wisconsin rejected HyperPhrase's claims that both AdSense and the AutoLink feature of Google's Web browser toolbar infringed on four of the tech firm's patents. The patents were specifically related to the way that an application
creates links between text fragments and assorted documents, and the way that information is then presented to viewers. As part of Google
Toolbar, AutoLink provides users with more than just standard links when they search for info--the feature recognizes data like addresses or International Standard Book Numbers (ISBNs) and provides links to online maps or books on Amazon.com. The district court issued a summary judgment in Google's favor for
the entire suit, and the court of appeals upheld the ruling as it
pertained to AdSense. But the Feds instructed the lower court to reexamine part of HyperPhrase's claim that the AutoLink feature infringed on two of its patents, citing the state's "inappropriate interpretation" of terms used in the tech firm's patent filings. So while AdSense is in the clear, Google Toolbar and its use of
AutoLink will have to stand up to HyperPhrase's claims in the state court under a different kind of scrutiny (as suggested by the Feds). In a statement, Google lawyer Michael Kwun said that the company was
pleased that the Federal court upheld the AdSense ruling in their favor, but added: "We continue to believe the remaining claims in the lawsuit are without merit, and will vigorously defend against those claims." Tameka Kee can be reached at tameka@mediapost.com Today's Most Read 1. NBC U, As In University: Peacock Net Heads To College 2. Facebook's Scrabulous Under Fire From Hasbro 3. Just An Online Minute... The Cruise Clip That Won't Die 4. Hyundai Looking For Brand-Boosting Halo In Genesis 5. Ad It Up: ABC Considers Fate Of Oscar Spots Recent Online Media Daily Articles Facebook's Scrabulous Under Fire From Hasbro Jan 16, 7:00 AM Since surfacing on the site in June, an application that lets people play Scrabble online has... Digital Agency Veteran Bader Joins BrandinHand Jan 16, 7:00 AM Digital agency veteran Eric Bader has joined mobile marketing consultancy BrandinHand as president and managing director... MessageLabs Brings Computer Threats To Life In Campaign Jan 16, 7:00 AM If you've ever wondered what a computer virus or Trojan really looks like, MessageLabs has the... Oprah, Discovery Team For Multi-Platform Network Jan 16, 7:00 AM Health and wellness Web destinations can expect some serious competition in the second half of 2009,... Ad Network Targets College Students Jan 16, 7:00 AM Advanced Student Marketing, the online network targeting college students, has launched a multichannel, vertical ad network.... Online Values Seen As Bubblish, Social Nets Most 'Overhyped' Jan 16, 7:00 AM Nearly two-thirds (62%) of senior executives at major U.S. media companies believe a "bubble" is looming... Microsoft and MediaCart Partner For Supermarket Video Ads Jan 15, 8:30 AM Computerized shopping cart maker MediaCart Holdings has enlisted Microsoft's Atlas Division to deliver targeted video ads... Report: ValueClick Lead-Gen Practices Still Flawed Jan 15, 8:30 AM ValueClick said it hopes to settle a Federal Trade Commission probe into its lead-generation business by