      Article Home Investing News Top News UK World Business Sports Football Cricket Rugby Union Golf Tennis Motor Sports Technology Entertainment Science & Health Environment Motoring Oddly Enough Lifestyle Video Pictures Blogs Weather Editor's Choice Do More With Reuters RSS Mobile Podcasts Newsletters Desktop Alerts Interactive TV Professional Products Financial Media Support (Customer Zone) About Reuters Tennis-Fifth-seed Peer advances at Australian Hardcourt champs Sun Dec 30, 2007 9:17am GMT Email | Print | Share | Single Page | [ - ] Text [ + ] MELBOURNE, Dec 30 (Reuters) - Fifth-seeded Israeli Shahar
Peer overcame a sluggish start before advancing to the second
round of the Australian Hardcourt championships on the Gold
Coast on Sunday. The world number 17 dropped the first set before finally
overcoming Julie Ditty of the United States 3-6 6-0 6-2 to set
up a second-round meeting with the winner of the match between
Lourdes Dominguez Lino and a qualifier. "Julie was playing good and she's not even in the top 100,"
Peer told reporters. "I had a lot of trouble with her. Every
match I have to play good." There were only two other first round matches on Sunday
with France's Nathalie Dechy beating China's Zi Yan 6-2 6-2,
while Belarussia's Victoria Azarenka beat two-time Gold Coast
champion Ai Sugiyama of Japan 6-2 6-3. France's Amelie Mauresmo, the 2006 Australian Open and
Wimbledon champion, will play her first round match on Monday
against Olga Savchuk of Ukraine, while top seed Nicole
Vaidisova of the Czech Republic will meet local wildcard Casey
Dellacqua. Vaidisova and Mauresmo are scheduled to meet in the
semi-finals of the tournament that runs until Jan. 5. The Australian Open, the year's first grand slam, runs from
Jan. 14-27.
